        {
          "type": "frame",
          "id": "l2hWL",
          "name": "WhySAS",
          "width": "fill_container",
          "layout": "vertical",
          "gap": "$space-4",
          "children": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "id": "Xc38m",
              "name": "Heading",
              "fill": "$ink",
              "content": "Why SAS exists alongside SATA",
              "fontFamily": "$font-serif",
              "fontSize": "$size-30",
              "fontWeight": "$w-semibold"
            },
            {
              "type": "frame",
              "id": "vBuuo",
              "name": "Body",
              "width": "fill_container",
              "gap": "$space-6",
              "children": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "Ijgxx",
                  "name": "Prose",
                  "fill": "$ink-muted",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "The split is ancestral. SATA descends from parallel ATA — the desktop lineage; SAS (Serial Attached SCSI) descends from parallel SCSI — the server lineage. When both went serial they deliberately shared the connector and signaling, so a SAS controller can drive SATA disks, but never the reverse. That one-way compatibility is why an HBA future-proofs the build: it eats both interfaces, and you chase whichever is cheaper per deal.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.5,
                  "fontFamily": "$font-sans",
                  "fontSize": "$size-13",
                  "fontWeight": "$w-regular"
                },
                {
